; model-retire.form — the supervision endgame, told in Lisp-comment voice.
;
; ----------------------------------------------------------------------
; PURPOSE
; ----------------------------------------------------------------------
; A borrowed third-party model rides the route as the CHAMPION while a
; Form-native body learns the same job as the CHALLENGER. The challenger
; trains; the scoreboard accumulates who was right. This brick answers the
; one question that closes the loop: may we now FREE the borrowed model?
;
; Retirement is the supervision endgame — the moment the native body has
; earned the route outright. It is deliberately conservative: a lucky
; streak on a handful of samples is not a verdict. The challenger must
; lead by a clear MARGIN over a long ENOUGH window before the champion is
; let go.
;
;   scoreboard = (list champ-wins  chall-wins  samples)
;
; ----------------------------------------------------------------------
; FUNCTIONS
; ----------------------------------------------------------------------
;   (mr-champ   sb)  → champ-wins     ; nth sb 0
;   (mr-chall   sb)  → chall-wins     ; nth sb 1
;   (mr-samples sb)  → samples        ; nth sb 2
;
;   (mr-decisive? sb min-samples margin) → 1 | 0
;       1 iff BOTH gates hold:
;         enough evidence   samples    >= min-samples
;         clear lead        chall-wins >= champ-wins + margin
;
;   (mr-retire?        sb min-samples margin) → 1 | 0   ; == mr-decisive?
;   (mr-keep-champion? sb min-samples margin) → 1 | 0   ; strict inverse
;
; mr-retire? and mr-keep-champion? partition every scoreboard: for any
; (sb, min, margin), retire? + keep? == 1 — no gap, no overlap.
;
; ----------------------------------------------------------------------
; SPINE-COMPOSITION
; ----------------------------------------------------------------------
; Everything is count-and-gate; the spine is the decisive predicate and
; the two questions hang off it:
;
;   mr-retire?  ─┐
;                ├─> mr-decisive?  ─> (and  gate-evidence  gate-lead)
;   mr-keep-... ─┘                         │              │
;                                          │              └─ (ge chall (add champ margin))
;                                          └─ (ge samples min-samples)
;
;   accessors:  mr-champ / mr-chall / mr-samples  =  (nth sb {0,1,2})
;
; Two trap-dodges carry the whole shape:
;
;   - No subtraction. "Challenger beat champion by >= margin" is NOT
;     `(ge (sub chall champ) margin)` — there is no `sub`. It is the
;     equivalent ADD-gate `(ge chall (add champ margin))`: push the
;     margin onto the champion's side and compare. Same arithmetic truth,
;     only count + compare primitives — the same move classifier-eval.fk
;     uses to turn a ratio into a proven-count gate.
;
;   - `and` is BINARY. The two gates are one nested `(and a b)`; a third
;     condition would have to nest again, never `(and a b c)` (Go and Rust
;     drop the third arm, TS folds it — a real divergence).
;
; mr-keep-champion? is `(if (eq (mr-decisive? ...) 1) 0 1)` rather than a
; second independent computation, so the inverse can never drift out of
; sync with the gate it negates — the partition invariant holds by
; construction, and the band proves it (retire? + keep? == 1).
;
; ----------------------------------------------------------------------
; ONE HONEST LANE
; ----------------------------------------------------------------------
; This recipe DECIDES retirement from a scoreboard of integer tallies. It
; does not run the contest, score a single sample, or update the
; scoreboard — those live upstream in the supervision loop. Given honest
; integer tallies it answers deterministically and identically across the
; Go, Rust, and TypeScript kernels.
;
; PROOF: form/validate.sh over
;   form-stdlib/core.fk  form-stdlib/model-retire.fk
;   form-stdlib/tests/model-retire-band.fk
; → verdict 63 (six bits), 1 ok, 0 divergent — the three kernels agree on
; the decisive win, the thin-lead keep, the exact margin boundary, the
; one-sample-short keep, and the partition invariant from both sides.